/line></svg></div></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>When high-ranking=
 monkeys were =E2=80=9Cknocked out=E2=80=9D (as the scientists called it), =
conflict and aggression soared. After the leaders were removed, the group h=
ad fewer grooming interactions and played less frequently. Social ties disi=
ntegrated. =E2=80=9CThis suggests that stable leadership promotes peaceful =
interactions not only between leaders and followers,=E2=80=9D Christakis wr=
ites, =E2=80=9Cbut also between followers and other followers.=E2=80=9D </p=
><p>When the monkey leaders were in place, they intervened between status-s=
eekers and regulated social connections. Lower-ranking monkeys knew that if=
 conflict arose, the higher-ranking monkeys would step in. The presence of =
leaders allowed lower-ranking monkeys to interact with one another without =
fear of attack. When the leaders were removed, the macaques began jockeying=
 for power, which resulted in mayhem and violence.</p><div><hr></div><p>Wha=
t about for humans?</p><p><span>In the second year of my doctoral program I=
